Analyzing Bangladeshi Election Data

Nasheya Rahman

The goal of this project is to analyze Bangladeshi election data and figure out what kinds of factors may have contributed to certain liberal or conservative parties being elected. There are two main parties in Bangladesh - Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) and Awami League. BNP is significantly more conservative than Awami League, and the elections that BNP was elected may reflect the rising conservatism in Bangladesh.

The factors Ill be looking at are urbanization and labor migrant populations. In the future, I hope to look at education levels and religiousness in the country. The goal is to be able to explain the differences in the parties elected from one election to another and then possibly be able to forecast to see what the future would look like.

Of course, politics are very nuanced, especially in a country like Bangladesh where there may be voter fraud going on and the election system is, essentially, considered to be broken. This project is more supposed to be some kind of preliminary analysis because the deeper analysis would be something more like what a PhD student would do.

Political Parties

Just a small lesson on the political parties of Bangladesh and what they mean.

Awami League

One of the two major parties in Bangladesh. Theyre the left-wing, secular, democratic party of Bangladesh.

Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)

This is the other major party in Bangladesh. Theyre the right-wing, conservative party of Bangladesh.

Jamaat-e-Islami Party

This is the largest Islamist party in Bangladesh and they strongly opposed the independence from Pakistan because they believe that Islamic nations should be united. They were considered unfit to participate in national elections as they were, so they had to revamp their party.

Jatiya Party

Historically conservative, Jatiya Party splintered off into two groups - one right-wing and one left-wing after there was a disagreement of the chairs of the party.

Grand Alliance (Mohajote) and 18-Party Alliance

These are the current day major parties, and theyre led by Awami League and BNP, respectively. Theyre both coalitions of parties that started collaborating and conglomerating. 4-Party Alliance is the predecessor of 18-Party Alliance.

Data

In my data, Im going to divide the data up into conservative and liberal. Under conservative will be the 18-Party Alliance parties and under liberal will be the Grand Alliance parties. Under Grand Alliance, I am considering the tags Awami League and Mohajote. Under 18-Party Alliance, I am considering BNP, Jatiya Party, Jamaat-e-Islami Party, and 4-Party Alliance.

Election Data

For the election data, Ill be looking at parliamentary elections. I have data for 4 different elections and the 1996 6th parliamentary election and the 2014 election data is missing. Whenever the data was missing though, it was when most of the opposition parties boycotted the elections, so a party ended up winning almost by default.

1991 Election Data:

attach(election1991)
election1991_temp <- aggregate(election1991[c(-1:-5, seq(-7, -17, by = -2), -18)], by = list(election1991$district), FUN=sum, na.rm=TRUE)
colnames(election1991_temp) = c("district", "total_votes", "AL_votes", "BNP_votes", "JP_votes", "JIB_votes", "others_votes")

election1991_temp$conservative_percent_1991 <- (election1991_temp$BNP_votes + election1991_temp$JIB_votes + election1991_temp$JP_votes)/election1991_temp$total_votes
election1991_temp$liberal_percent_1991 <- election1991_temp$AL_votes/election1991_temp$total_votes
election1991_temp$other_percent_1991 <- election1991_temp$others_votes/election1991_temp$total_votes
election1991_temp$conservative_chairs_1991 <- 0
election1991_temp$liberal_chairs_1991 <- 0
election1991_temp$other_chairs_1991 <- 0

districts_1991 <- election1991_temp$district

for(i in districts_1991){
  temp <- table(election1991$winner[election1991$district == i])
  
  for(j in names(temp)){
    tempNum <- temp[j]
    if(j %in% liberal){
      election1991_temp$liberal_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] <- election1991_temp$liberal_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] + tempNum
    } else if(j %in% conservative){
      election1991_temp$conservative_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] <- election1991_temp$conservative_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] + tempNum
    } else {
      election1991_temp$other_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] <- election1991_temp$other_chairs_1991[election1991_temp$district == i] + tempNum
    }
  }
}

detach(election1991)

For the urbanization data, I have the district census populations from 1991, 2001, and 2011 and the division and country populations every 10 years from 1901 to 2011. The numbers are in millions. If we look at the district populations ranks though, we see that most districts stayed very close to what they initially were, so it looks like the population ratios didnt change that much.

qplot(rank_2011, rank_1991, data = district_pop)

However, a lot of information is lost with ranks. For example, Dhaka (the capital) is always rank #1, but that doesnt tell you how much more people moved to Dhaka than from the rural areas.

In order to try and measure urbanization, Im looking at the percentage change of the percent total of the population. So, for example, if in 1991 district A was 10% of the total population and in 2011, it was 5%, that means that the percentage change in the percentages of the total population at the time is -50%.

If we look at the plot of the percent changes from 1991 to 2011, well see that most areas actually lost mass while a few spots gained. This makes sense because most of Bangladesh is rural and the few spots that would be gaining would be the urban areas.

slope1 = (district_pop$pop_2001 - district_pop$pop_1991)/10
intercept1 = district_pop$pop_1991 - 1991*slope1

for(i in seq(1991, 2001)){
  ratio <- paste("ratio", i, sep="_")
  pop <- paste("pop", i, sep="_")
  district_pop[, pop] <- slope1*i + intercept1
  district_pop[, ratio] <- district_pop[, pop]/sum(district_pop[, pop])
}

slope2 = (district_pop$pop_2011 - district_pop$pop_2001)/10
intercept2 = district_pop$pop_2001 - 2001*slope2

for(i in seq(2002, 2011)){
  ratio <- paste("ratio", i, sep="_")
  pop <- paste("pop", i, sep="_")
  district_pop[, pop] <- slope2*i + intercept2
  district_pop[, ratio] <- district_pop[, pop]/sum(district_pop[, pop])
}

electionYears <- c(1996, 2001, 2008)
iPast <- 1991

for(i in electionYears){
  ratio <- paste("ratio", i, sep="_")
  ratioPast <- paste("ratio", iPast, sep="_")
  district_pop[, paste("percent_change", iPast, i, sep="_")] = (district_pop[, ratio]- district_pop[, ratioPast])/ district_pop[, ratioPast]
  iPast <- i
}
qplot(percent_change_1991_1996, data = district_pop)

Conclusion

Overall, the models with conservative chairs arent really good at all and I presume thats because theres one variable. However, surprisingly, the percentages are really predictive with the labor migrant populations! (That might totally be that theres like 4 data points.) Next step would be to incorporate other data and work with that instead.

Also, lessons learned - prepping your data is really hard.
